LEGIONELLOSIS, FATAL - UK (02): (SCOTLAND)
******************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 1 Jun 2011
Source: Wishaw Press [edited]
http://www.wishawpress.co.uk/wishaw-news/local-wishaw-news/wishaw-news/2011/06/01/legionnaires-bug-found-in-wishaw-sports-centre-76495-28796966/


Wishaw Sports Centre closed its doors last week after the bug, which
can cause the potentially fatal Legionnaires' disease, was found.
Leisure bosses were left with no option but to shut down the busy
facility after the bacteria were detected in the plumbing system on
Wednesday evening [25 May 2011]. _Legionella_ was picked up on shower
heads and taps in the centre's dry side changing areas during routine
testing -- which happens once a month -- and on advice from the Health
and Safety Executive the building was immediately shut.

Fitness fans were forced elsewhere all day Thursday [26 May 2011] as
a "comprehensive cleaning process" of the centre's water system was
undertaken and the centre opened again on Friday [27 May 2011].
Legionnaires' disease is a potentially fatal form of pneumonia caused
by the bacterium _Legionella pneumophila_ and carries the same
symptoms as a normal flu.

When the Wishaw Press went to print yesterday (Tuesday 31 May 2011),
there had been no cases of Legionnaires' disease in the area. The
advice given by Wishaw Sports Centre to members calling last week was
to check with your local GP if you are feeling unwell.

A spokesman for North Lanarkshire Leisure said: "As part of our
routine testing and prevention programme, we discovered a small number
of elevated _Legionella_ readings in the dry side area of the sports
centre.

"We work closely with the Health and Safety Executive at all times
and as soon as we became aware of the situation, we agreed to
voluntarily close the centre yesterday evening (Wed 25 May 2011) for
further investigation and treatment of the areas concerned. Where
possible we notified our customers and apologised to them for any
inconvenience caused. Their health and safety and that of our staff is
our prime concern."

The Health and Safety Executive were staying tight-lipped when
quizzed last week, saying: "North Lanarkshire Leisure are cooperating
with the Health and Safety Executive in a health investigation."

[Byline: Euan McLelland]

