[The isolation of _Legionella_ from the plumbing system at the Wishaw
Sports Centre in North Lanarkshire, Scotland was said to be the result
of routine monthly testing, and not the result of an outbreak
investigation; both news releases above state that there were no cases
of Legionnaires' disease as a result of the _Legionella_ discovered
within the sports centre. However, the 2nd news release fails to say
why the employee of the Wishaw Sports Centre is thought to have
acquired his illness as a result of the Glasgow outbreak of
Legionnaires' disease and not as a result of exposure at the sports
center.

According to a prior ProMED-mail post (Legionellosis, fatal - UK:
(Scotland) 20110514.1472), there were 7 confirmed cases of
Legionnaires' disease, including 3 deaths, in Greater Glasgow,
Scotland. The 2nd news release above says there are 9 cases who live
within the Greater Glasgow and Clyde, and Lanarkshire health board
areas. The additional patient mentioned above may be the 10th case in
that outbreak.

We still do not know if there is a link between the cases, and we do
not know if there is a species of _Legionella_ common among the
Glasgow cases or if so, if there is a common genotype among the
isolates of the organism. The predominance of one genotype in patient
specimens would suggest transmission from a common source. Frequently,
however, this is difficult in legionellosis outbreaks because the
diagnosis of Legionnaires' disease is made only on the basis of
urinary _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1 antigen testing or serology,
rather than isolation of the organism from cultures of respiratory
tract specimens, in which case genotyping of clinical isolates is, of
course, not possible.

The Wishaw Sports Centre in North Lanarkshire is southeast of the
City of Glasgow
(http://maps.google.com/maps?client=safari&rls=en&q=wishaw+sports+centre+map&oe=UTF-8&um=1&ie=UTF-8&hq=&hnear=0x4888132524605a65:0x4ea9e951718c74a4,Wishaw+Sports+Centre&gl=us&ei=fdzyTbm0OMyugQe8jrziCw&sa=X&oi=geocode_result&ct=image&resnum=1&ved=0CBcQ8gEwAA.
North Lanarkshire contains much of Glasgow's suburbs and commuter
towns and villages (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Lanarkshire).
Greater Glasgow, which consists of all localities that are physically
attached to the city of Glasgow, had a population of 1 199 629 at the
2001 census (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater_Glasgow). NHS
Greater Glasgow and Clyde is a National Health Service board in West
Central Scotland, created from the amalgamation of NHS Greater Glasgow
and part of NHS Argyll and Clyde. It is the largest health board in
the United Kingdom
(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NHS_Greater_Glasgow_and_Clyde).

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Scotland is available at
http://healthmap.org/r/0YMP. A more detailed map of the Glasgow area
of Scotland can be found at
http://www.gosur.com/en/scotland/glasgow/glasgow_map/. - Mod.ML]
